result.execSummary:
The defendant Brandon Scott Wagener was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Battery [Modifiers: Repeater, Domestic Abuse Assessments], a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 940.19(1).
  • Disorderly Conduct [Modifiers: Domestic Abuse Assessments, Repeater], a class B misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 947.01(1).
  • Intimidate Victim/Use or Attempt Force [Modifiers: Domestic Abuse Assessments], a class G felony, Wisconsin Statutes 940.45(1).
  • Possess/Illegally Obtained Prescription [Modifiers: Repeater], an unclassified misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 450.11(7)(h).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Brandon Scott Wagener in court with attorney Lori Ann Kuehn.  Robert Scott Repischak appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Court Reporter: Patricia Schaefer.
Defense has an objection to the State's request for other acts. Defense feels it would be unfair prejudice. Defense does not have an objection to the party the State wishes to identify as an expert.

The State has provided the State with copies of text messages between the parties and Mr. Repischak will forward same to Ms. Sommers

BTC: The Court rejects that it is panoramic evidence, second prong of Sullivan is met and the third prong is met as well. The Court will allow the introduction of these attacks or alleged attacks in this incident. The Court will defer ruling on the reference to a broken nose unless there is information that can substantiate said information. The Court will defer ruling on the incident in paragraph #3. The Court believes if the victim and the State are able to provide specific dates and times, the Court may allow information regarding the statement that "as soon as her face heals, he hits her again". The Court will reserve ruling subject to the State providing, dates, times and frequency. The Court will not allow the blanket statement by the victim that deft began to abuse her shortly after they began living together nor will the Court will allow the statement that deft hit her on her head so her hair would cover it. The statement that deft held a knife to her throat and threatened her and her family is not other acts; it is the basis for Ct 6. Matter will be revisited prior to voir dire. The Court is satisfied, by looking at the documents submitted by the State, that the party the State wishes to identify as an expert may testify in that capacity, however this Court will not certify any witness as an expert.
